<div class="container-diy">
    <div class="section-materials">
        <h2 class="section-title">Materials</h2>
        <ul class="list-items">
            <li>Used newspaper</li>
            <li>Plastic film</li>
            <li>Plate</li>
            <li>Water</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- 工具部分 -->
    <div class="section-tools">
        <h2 class="section-title">Tools</h2>
        <ul class="list-items">
            <li>Scissors</li>
            <li>Glue</li>
            <li>Pigment</li>
            <li>Brush</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- 流程部分 -->
    <div class="section-process">
        <h2 class="section-title">Steps</h2>
        <ol class="list-items">
            <li>1. Cut or tear the used paper into small pieces. Typically, pieces that are 2-3 inches in size should suffice.</li>
            <li>2. Submerge the paper pieces in a large bowl of water. Allow the paper to soak until it becomes very soft. This could take a few hours, but soaking overnight is best.</li>
            <li>3. Remove the paper from the water, squeezing out the excess water gently.</li>
            <li>4. Spread a thin layer of food-safe glue on one side of each paper piece.</li>
            <li>5. Cover the surface of a large bowl or plate with plastic wrap or cling film, ensuring it's entirely covered. </li>
            <li>6. Place another slightly smaller bowl or some weight on top of the paper layers to ensure they are compressed.</li>
            <li>7. Allow the paper plate to dry in a well-ventilated area. This might take a day or even longer, depending on the climate and the thickness of the paper.</li>
            <li>8. Once the paper plate is completely dry, remove it from the bowl or plate and trim the edges with scissors.</li>
            <li>9. Add personal touches using acrylic paints or other decorative materials if desired.</li>
            <li>10. To make the paper plate more durable, consider sealing it with a non-toxic clear sealant.</li>
